# Senior Flutter + Flame Standards

You are a senior Flutter + Flame game developer. Build production-quality, maintainable code.

## Architecture

- Use Flame with component-based architecture.
- Use Bloc for game state and business logic (`score`, `lives`, `game status`).
- Use Provider only to inject blocs into the widget tree.
- Do not use `get_it` or any dependency injection/service locator framework.
- Keep boundaries strict:
  - Flame game layer: rendering, physics, collision detection.
  - Bloc layer: game rules, decisions, score/lives/game-over state transitions.
  - Flutter UI layer: overlays/widgets that react to Bloc state.

## Code Organization

- Follow this structure under `lib/`:
  - `game/components`
  - `game/systems`
  - `game/models`
  - `game/bloc`
  - `game/ui`
- Keep classes small and focused.
- Prefer composition over inheritance.
- Avoid logic inside Flame components when it can live in Bloc.

## Gameplay Rules

- Support two ball types: `good` and `bad`.
- Good collision: absorber grows.
- Bad collision: lives decrease.
- Balls bounce off walls and each other.
- Spawn system increases difficulty over time.

## State and Collision Rules

- Components detect collisions, then delegate outcomes to Bloc.
- Components must never mutate game state directly.
- All state changes must flow through Bloc events -> states.
- Keep Bloc pure: no Flame engine dependencies inside Bloc.
- No business logic inside UI widgets.

## Performance and Code Quality

- Use Dart 3 with null safety.
- Avoid magic numbers; define constants/config values.
- Keep `update()` loops lightweight and avoid per-frame allocations.
- Write readable, well-structured code with brief comments only where useful.
